llm_answer:
The reaction  

\[
\text{Mg(s)} + 2\;\text{HCl(aq)} \rightarrow \text{MgCl}_2\text{(aq)} + \text{H}_2\text{(g)}
\]

produces one mole of \( \text{H}_2 \) for each mole of Mg that reacts.

**Moles of Mg**

\[
n_{\text{Mg}}=\frac{15\ \text{g}}{M_{\text{Mg}}}= \frac{15}{24.31}\ \text{mol}=0.617\ \text{mol}
\]

Thus the amount of \( \text{H}_2 \) formed is  

\[
n_{\text{H}_2}=0.617\ \text{mol}
\]

**Volume of gas produced (ideal‑gas law, \(P=1.00\ \text{atm},\ T=298\ \text{K}\))**

\[
V=\frac{nRT}{P}= \frac{(0.617\ \text{mol})(0.082057\ \text{L·atm·K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1})(298\ \text{K})}{1.00\ \text{atm}}
      =15.1\ \text{L}
\]

**Work done by the system (expansion work)**  

\[
w = -P\Delta V = -(1.00\ \text{atm})(15.1\ \text{L}) = -15.1\ \text{atm·L}
\]

Converting \( \text{atm·L} \) to kilojoules (\(1\ \text{atm·L}=101.325\ \text{J}=0.101325\ \text{kJ}\)):

\[
w = -15.1\ \text{atm·L}\times 0.101325\ \frac{\text{kJ}}{\text{atm·L}}
    = -1.53\ \text{kJ}
\]

\[
\boxed{-1.53}\;\text{kJ}
\]

The entropy change for a reversible, isothermal heat transfer is  

\[
\Delta S=\frac{q_{\text{rev}}}{T}
\]

Here \(q_{\text{rev}} = 25\ \text{kJ}=2.50\times10^{4}\ \text{J}\) and the temperature of the iron block is  

\[
T = 0^{\circ}\text{C}=273.15\ \text{K}
\]

\[
\Delta S = \frac{2.50\times10^{4}\ \text{J}}{273.15\ \text{K}}
        \approx 9.16\times10^{1}\ \text{J K}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{9.16\times10^{1}} \,\text{J K}^{-?1}
\]

The ideal‑gas molar volume at the given conditions is  

\[
V_{m,\;{\rm ideal}}=\frac{RT}{P}
   =\frac{(0.082057\ \text{dm}^{3}\,\text{atm}\,\text{K}^{-1}\,\text{mol}^{-1})(250\ \text{K})}{15\ \text{atm}}
   =\frac{20.51425}{15}\ \text{dm}^{3}\,\text{mol}^{-1}
   \approx 1.368\ \text{dm}^{3}\,\text{mol}^{-1}.
\]

The actual molar volume is 12 % smaller:

\[
V_{m}=V_{m,\;{\rm ideal}}\,(1-0.12)=0.88\,V_{m,\;{\rm ideal}}
      =0.88\times1.368\ \text{dm}^{3}\,\text{mol}^{-1}
      \approx 1.20\ \text{dm}^{3}\,\text{mol}^{-1}.
\]

\[
\boxed{1.20}\ \mathrm{dm^{3}\ mol^{-1}}
\]

The entropy change of the surroundings for the vaporisation at the normal boiling point is  

\[
\Delta S_{\text{surr}} = -\frac{\Delta H_{\text{vap}}}{T_{\text{}}}
                       = -frac{29.4\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}\times 10^{3}\;\text{J kJ}^{-1}}
                               {334.88\;\text{K}}
                       = -87.8\;\text{J K}^{-1}\text{ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{-87.8}\ \mathrm{J\ K^{-1}\ mol^{-1}}
\]

\[
P=\frac{nRT}{V}
=\frac{(1.0\ \text{mol})(0.08206\ \tfrac{\text{L·atm}}{\text{mol·K}})(298\ \text{K})}{1.0\ \text{L}}
\approx 24.5\ \text{atm}
\]

\[
\boxed{24.5}\ \text{atm}
\]

\[
\Delta S = -\left(\frac{\partial \Delta G}{\partial T}\right)_{p}
           = -\,36.5\;\text{J K}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{-36.5}\;\text{J K}^{-1}
\]

The heat supplied at constant pressure is related to the molar heat capacity by  

\[
q = n\,C_{p,m}\,\Delta T \; \Longrightarrow; 
C_{p,m}= \frac{q}{n\Delta T}
\]

\[
n\Delta T = (3.0\ \text{mol})(2.55\ \text{K}) = 7.65\ \text{mol·K}
\]

\[
C_{p,m}= \frac{229\ \text{J}}{7.65\ \text{mol·K}} \approx 30\ \text{J K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{30}\ \text{J K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1}
\]

The de Broglie wavelength of a particle is  

\[
\lambda=\frac{h}{p},\qquad p=\sqrt{2m_{e}K},
\]

where \(h=6.62607015\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s}\), \(m_{e}=9.10938356\times10^{-31}\,\text{kg}\) and the kinetic energy \(K=100\ \text{eV}=100\times1.602176634\times10^{-19}\,\text{J}=1.6022\times10^{-17}\,\text{J}\).

\[
\begin{aligned}
p &=\sqrt{2m_{e}K}
   =\sqrt{2(9.10938356\times10^{-31})(1.6022\times10^{-17})}\\
  &\approx 5.40\times10^{-24}\ \text{kg·m s}^{-1}.
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
\lambda=\frac{6.62607015\times10^{-34}}{5.40\times10^{-24}}
        \approx 1.23\times10^{-10}\ \text{m}
        =0.123\ \text{nm}.
\]

\[
\boxed{0.12}\ \text{nm}
\]

The series limit of the Lyman series corresponds to a transition from \(n=\infty\) to \(n=1\) in the hydrogen atom.  
Using the Rydberg formula  

\[
\frac{1}{\lambda}=R_{\infty}\!\left(\frac{1}{1^{2}}-\frac{1}{\infty^{2}}\right)=R_{\infty},
\]

where \(R_{\infty}=1.097\,373\,1568\times10^{7}\;\text{m}^{-1}\).

---

### Wavelength

\[
\lambda=\frac{1}{R_{\infty}}
        =\frac{1}{1.097\,373\,1568\times10^{7}}
        =9.1127\times10^{-8}\;\text{m}
        =9.1127\times10^{-8}\;\text{m}\times10^{9}\;\frac{\text{nm}}{\text{m}}
        =\boxed{91.13}\ \text{nm}
\]

---

### Energy

\[
E=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
   =\frac{(6.626\,070\,15\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s})
          (2.997\,924\,58\times10^{8}\,\text{m·s}^{-1})}
          {9.1127\times10^{-8}\,\text{m}}
   =2.18\times10^{-18}\;\text{J}
   =\boxed{13.60}\ \text{eV}
\]

\[
\nu = \frac{c}{\lambda}= \frac{2.998\times 10^{8}\ \text{m s}^{-1}}{632.8\times10^{-9}\ \text{m}}
      = 4.74\times10^{14}\ \text{Hz}
\]

\[
\boxed{4.74}\times10^{14}\ \text{Hz}
\]

The energy of one photon at \(\lambda = 1.06\;\mu\text{m}\) is  

\[
E_{\text{ph}}=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
          =\frac{(6.626\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s})(3.00\times10^{8}\,\text{m/s})}
                 {1.06\times10^{-6}\,\text{m}}
          \approx 1.88\times10^{-19}\ \text{J}.
\]

The pulse contains an energy of \(E_{\text{pulse}} = 2.00\ \text{mJ}=2.00\times10^{-3}\ \text{J}\).

Hence the number of photons in the pulse is  

\[
N=\frac{E_{\text{pulse}}}{E_{\text{ph}}}
  =\frac{2.00\times10^{-3}}{1.88\times10^{-19}}
  \approx 1.07\times10^{16}.
\]

\[
\boxed{1.07}\times10^{16}\ \text{photons}
\]

question:
$$
\text {Calculate the energy of a photon for a wavelength of } 100 \mathrm{pm} \text { (about one atomic diameter). }
$$

llm_answer:
\[
E=\frac{hc}{\lambda}= \frac{(6.62607015\times10^{-34}\ \mathrm{J\;s})(2.99792458\times10^{8}\ \mathrm{m/s})}{100\ \mathrm{pm}}
=1.986\times10^{-15}\ \mathrm{J}
\]

\[
\boxed{1.99}\times10^{-15}\ \mathrm{J}
\]

\[
\boxed{54.4}\;\text{eV}
\qquad\text{and}\qquad
\boxed{5.25\times10^{3}}
\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{7.6 \times 10^{1}}\ \text{J}
\]

The calorimeter constant \(C_{\text{cal}}\) is obtained from the benzoic‑acid calibration:

\[
\begin{aligned}
n_{\text{BA}} &= \frac{0.825\ \text{g}}{M_{\text{BA}}}= \frac{0.825}{122.12}=6.76\times10^{-3}\ \text{mol}\\[2mm]
q_{\text{BA}} &= n_{\text{BA}}\; \Delta_{\mathrm c}U_{\text{BA}}
               = (6.76\times10^{-3}\,\text{mol})(-3251\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1})
               = -21.97\ \text{kJ}\\[2mm]
C_{\text{cal}} &= \frac{|q_{\text{BA}}|}{\Delta T_{\text{BA}}}
                =\frac{21.97\ \text{kJ}}{1.940\ \text{K}}
                = 11.33\ \text{kJ K}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

For the ribose combustion:

\[
\begin{aligned}
n_{\text{rib}} &= \frac{0.727\ \text{g}}{M_{\text{rib}}}
               = \frac{0.727}{150.13}=4.84\times10^{-3}\ \text{mol} \\[2mm]
q_{\text{rib}} &= C_{\text{cal}}\;\Delta T_{\text{rib}}
               = (11.33\ \text{kJ K}^{-1})(0.910\ \text{K})
               = -10.31\ \text{kJ}\\[2mm]
\Delta_{\mathrm c}U_{\text{rib}} &= \frac{q_{\text{rib}}}{n_{\text{rib}}}
                                 = \frac{-10.31\ \text{kJ}}{4.84\times10^{-3}\ \text{mol}}
                                 = -2.13\times10^{3}\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

The combustion reaction is  

\[
\mathrm{C_5H_{10}O_5(s)}+5\ \mathrm{O_2(g)}\rightarrow 5\ \mathrm{CO_2(g)}+5\ \mathrm{H_2O(l)}
\]

Since \(\Delta n_{\text{gas}} = 5-5 =0\), \(\Delta_{\mathrm c}H = \Delta_{\mathrm c}U = -2.13\times10^{3}\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}\).

Using standard formation enthalpies (\(\Delta_f H^\circ\)) of the products:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\sum \nu\,\Delta_f H^\circ(\text{products})
&=5(-393.5)+5(-285.8)\\
&= -3396.5\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

Now  

\[
\Delta_f H^\circ(\text{ribose}) = 
\sum \nu\,\Delta_f H^\circ(\text{products}) - \Delta_{\mathrm c}H^\circ
= -3396.5 - (-2129.6) = -1267\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{-1.27\times10^{3}} \ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

The photon energy from the He‑lamp is  

\[
E_{\text{photon}}=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
   =\frac{(6.626\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s})(2.998\times10^{8}\,\text{m·s}^{-1})}
          {58.4\times10^{-9}\,\text{m}}
   =3.40\times10^{-18}\,\text{J}
\]

The kinetic energy of the emitted electron is  

\[
K=\frac12mv^{2}
   =\frac12(9.109\times10^{-31}\,\text{kg})(1.59\times10^{6}\,\text{m·s}^{-1})^{2}
   =1.15\times10^{-18}\,\text{J}
\]

The ionization (binding) energy of Kr is the difference  

\[
\text{IE}=E_{\text{photon}}-K
        =3.40\times10^{-18}\,\text{J}-1.15\times10^{-18}\,\text{J}
        =2.25\times10^{-18}\,\text{J}
\]

Converting to electron‑volts \(\left(1\;\text{eV}=1.602\times10^{-19}\,\text{J}\right)\),

\[
\text{IE}=\frac{2.25\times10^{-18}\;\text{J}}{1.602\times10^{-19}\;\text{J/eV}}
        \approx 1.40\times10^{1}\;\text{eV}=14.0\;\text{eV}
\]

\[
\boxed{14.0}\;\text{eV}
\]

The energy of a photon of wavelength \(\lambda\) is  

\[
E_{\text{photon}}=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
\]

where  

\(h = 6.626\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s}\),  
\(c = 2.998\times10^{8}\,\text{m·s}^{-1}\),  
\(\lambda = 300\ \text{nm}=3.00\times10^{-7}\,\text{m}\).

\[
E_{\text{photon}}=\frac{6.626\times10^{-34}\times2.998\times10^{8}}{3.00\times10^{-7}}
               =6.62\times10^{-19}\,\text{J}
\]

Energy per mole of photons:

\[
E_{\text{mol}} = N_{\!A}\,E_{\text{photon}}
               = (6.022\times10^{23}\,\text{mol}^{-1})(6.62\times10^{-19}\,\text{J})
               =3.99\times10^{5}\,\text{J·mol}^{-1}
               =3.99\times10^{2}\,\text{kJ·mol}^{-1}
\]

Thus the photon energy is essentially \( \approx 399\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}\), which is comparable to a typical single‑bond energy of \(400\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}\).

\[
\boxed{399}\ \text{kJ/mol}
\]

**Step‑by‑step**

1. **Fraction of genes that encode proteins**  

\[
f=\frac{\text{protein‑coding genes}}{\text{total genes}}
   =\frac{484}{523}\approx 0.925\;(92.5\%)
\]

\[
\boxed{\frac{484}{523}}\;\text{or}\;\boxed{0.925}
\]

2. **Other genes** – the remaining \(523-484=39\) genes most likely code for non‑protein products such as rRNA, tRNA, other functional RNAs, or regulatory small proteins.

3. **Average number of base pairs per protein‑coding gene**  

Assuming the same fraction of the genome is devoted to protein‑coding DNA,

\[
\text{bp}_{\text{protein}} = f \times 580\,074\;\text{bp}
                         =\frac{484}{523}\times580\,074
                         \approx 5.368\times10^{5}\;\text{bp}
\]

\[
\text{average bp/gene}= \frac{\text{bp}_{\text{protein}}}{484}
                      =\frac{5.368\times10^{5}}{484}
                      \approx 1.11\times10^{3}\;\text{bp}
\]

\[
\boxed{1.11\times10^{3}\ \text{bp}}
\]

4. **Average number of amino acids per protein**  

Each amino acid is specified by a codon of 3 bp,

\[
\text{aa}_{\text{avg}} = \frac{1.11\times10^{3}\ \text{bp}}{3\ \text{bp/aa}}
                       \approx 3.70\times10^{2}\ \text{aa}
\]

\[
\boxed{3.70\times10^{2}\ \text{aa}}
\]

5. **Mass of an average protein**  

Average residue mass ≈ 120 Da,

\[
M_{\text{protein}} = 3.70\times10^{2}\ \text{aa}\times120\ \frac{\text{Da}}{\text{aa}}
                   \approx 4.44\times10^{4}\ \text{Da}
\]

\[
\boxed{4.44\times10^{4}\ \text{Da}}
\]

For a weak acid \( \text{HA} \) :

\[
\ce{HA <=> H^{+} + A^{-}},\qquad K_a=\frac{[\ce{H^{+}}][\ce{A^{-}}]}{[\ce{HA}]}
\]

Let \(x=[\ce{H^{+}}]=[\ce{A^{-}}]\) and \([\ce{HA}] = 0.10-x\).  

\[
K_a = \frac{x^{2}}{0.10-x}
\]

Because \(K_a\) is small, \(x \ll 0.10\) and we may approximate \(0.10-x\approx 0.10\):

\[
x \approx \sqrt{K_a \times 0.10}
      = \sqrt{(1.78\times10^{-4})(0.10)}
      = \sqrt{1.78\times10^{-5}}
      \approx 4.2\times10^{-3}\,\text{M}
\]

The pH is

\[
\text{pH}= -\log_{10}[\,\ce{H^{+}}\,] = -\log_{10}(4.2\times10^{-3})
        = 2.38\; .
\]

\[
\boxed{2.38}
\]

The increase in height is  

\[
\Delta h = 4\;\text{in}=4(2.54\;\text{cm})=10.16\;\text{cm}=1.016\times10^{8}\;\text{nm}
\]

A collagen triple‑helix advances one turn every  

\[
p = 0.86\ \text{nm (pitch per turn)}
\]

Hence the total number of helix turns formed in one year is  

\[
N_{\text{year}}=\frac{\Delta h}{p}= \frac{1.016\times10^{8}\ \text{nm}}{0.86\ \text{nm/turn}}
               \approx 1.18\times10^{8}\ \text{turns}
\]

One year contains  

\[
t_{\text{year}} = 365\ \text{days}\times 24\ \text{h day}^{-1}\times 60\ \text{min h}^{-1}
                = 5.256\times10^{5}\ \text{min}
\]

Therefore, the number of collagen helix turns synthesized per strand per minute is  

\[
\frac{N_{\text{year}}}{t_{\text{year}}}= 
\frac{1.18\times10^{8}}{5.256\times10^{5}}
\approx 2.3\times10^{2}\ \text{turns min}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{2.3\times10^{2}}\ \text{turns/min}
\]

The mass fractions are  

\[
\text{protein}=75\%,\qquad \text{lipid}=25\%
\]

Take \(100\; \text{g}\) of membrane:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\text{mass of protein} &=75\;\text{g}\\
\text{mass of lipid}   &=25\;\text{g}
\end{aligned}
\]

Moles of each component  

\[
\begin{aligned}
n_{\text{protein}} &=\frac{75\;\text{g}}{26\,000\;\text{g mol}^{-1}}
                    =\frac{75}{26\,000}\;\text{mol}
                    =2.88\times10^{-3}\;\text{mol}\\[4pt]
n_{\text{lipid}}   &=\frac{25\;\text{g}}{800\;\text{g mol}^{-1}}
                    =\frac{25}{800}\;\text{mol}
                    =3.125\times10^{-2}\;\text{mol}
\end{aligned}
\]

Mole ratio (phospholipid : protein)

\[
\frac{n_{\text{lipid}}}{n_{\text{protein}}}
=\frac{3.125\times10^{-2}}{2.8846\times10^{-3}}
\approx 10.8
\]

\[
\boxed{10.8}
\] (phospholipid : protein, dimensionless)

The Michaelis–Menten equation gives  

\[
v=\frac{V_{\max}[S]}{K_m+[S]}
      =\frac{(100\;\mu\text{mol}/\text{mL·sec})\times(20\;\text{mM})}{2\;\text{mM}+20\;\text{mM}}
