The cubic form of BN (zinc‑blende) has 4 formula units **BN** per conventional cubic cell.

\[
Z = 4
\]

Molar mass of BN  

\[
M_{\text{BN}} = M_{\text{B}} + M_{\text{N}} = 10.81\;\text{g mol}^{-1}+14.01\;\text{g mol}^{-1}=24.82\;\text{g mol}^{-1}
\]

Mass of one unit cell  

\[
m_{\text{cell}}= \frac{Z\,M_{\text{BN}}}{N_A}
          =\frac{4\times24.82\;\text{g mol}^{-1}}{6.022\times10^{23}\;\text{mol}^{-1}}
          =1.65\times10^{-22}\;\text{g}
\]

Cell edge length  

\[
a = 3.63\;\text{Å}=3.63\times10^{-8}\;\text{cm}
\]

Cell volume  

\[
V_{\text{cell}} = a^{3}= (3.63\times10^{-8}\,\text{cm})^{3}
                = 4.78\times10^{-23}\;\text{cm}^{3}
\]

Density  

\[
\rho = \frac{m_{\text{cell}}}{V_{\text{cell}}}
     = \frac{1.65\times10^{-22}\;\text{g}}{4.78\times10^{-23}\;\text{cm}^{3}}
     \approx 3.45\;\text{g cm}^{-3}
\]

\[
\boxed{3.45\ \text{g cm}^{-3}}
\]

The cubic unit‑cell volume is  

\[
V = a^{3}= \left(3.63\;\text{\AA}\right)^{3}
      = \left(3.63\times10^{-8}\,\text{cm}\right)^{3}
      = 3.63^{3}\times10^{-24}\,\text{cm}^{3}
      \approx 4.78\times10^{-23}\,\text{cm}^{3}.
\]

\[
\boxed{4.78\times10^{-23}}\ \text{cm}^{3}
\]

The dissolution equilibrium is  

\[
\ce{BaSO4(s) <=> Ba^{2+}(aq) + SO4^{2-}(aq)}
\]

If the molar solubility is \(s\;(\text{mol L}^{-1})\),

\[
K_{sp}= [\ce{Ba^{2+}}][\ce{SO4^{2-}}]=s^{2}
\]

\[
s=\sqrt{K_{sp}}=\sqrt{1.07\times10^{-10}}
        =1.03\times10^{-5}\ \text{mol L}^{-1}
\]

Molar mass of \(\ce{BaSO4}\):

\[
M=\;M_{\ce{Ba}}+M_{\ce{S}}+4M_{\ce{O}}
   =137.33+32.07+4(15.999)=233.4\ \text{g mol}^{-1}
\]

Mass of \(\ce{BaSO4}\) that dissolves per litre of water:

\[
m = sM = (1.03\times10^{-5}\,\text{mol L}^{-1})(233.4\ \text{g mol}^{-1})
      =2.4\times10^{-3}\ \text{g L}^{-1}
\]

Assuming the solution is dilute, \(1\;\text{L}\approx 1000\;\text{g}\) of water.  
Therefore, per 100 g of water:

\[
\frac{2.4\times10^{-3}\ \text{g}}{1000\ \text{g}}\times 100\ \text{g}
=2.4\times10^{-4}\ \text{g}
\]

\[
\boxed{2.4\times10^{-4}\ \text{g BaSO}_4\ \text{per}\ 100\ \text{g H}_2\text{O}}
\]

The reaction extent \(\xi\) equals the amount (in moles) of the fat that is oxidised.

\[
\begin{aligned}
M_{\text{fat}} &= 57(12.011)+104(1.008)+6(15.999) \\
               &= 885.5\ \text{g mol}^{-1}\\[4pt]
n_{\text{fat}}  &= \frac{1000\ \text{g}}{885.5\ \text{g mol}^{-1}}
                = 1.13\ \text{mol}
\end{aligned}
\]

Thus the reaction progress is  

\[
\boxed{1.13\ \text{mol}}
\]

The heat released is obtained from the standard enthalpy change of the reaction:

\[
q = \Delta_r H_{m}^{\ominus}\, n_{\text{fat}}
   = (-3.35\times10^{4}\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1})(1.13\ \text{mol})
   = -3.79\times10^{4}\ \text{kJ}
\]

(The negative sign indicates heat evolution; the magnitude of heat released is \(3.79\times10^{4}\) kJ.)

\[
\boxed{3.79\times10^{4}}\ \text{kJ}
\]

\[
\Delta_{r}H_{m}^{\ominus}\bigl(\ce{CO(g) + 2H_{2}(g) \rightarrow CH_{3}OH(l)}\bigr)= -128.5\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

The desired reaction can be obtained by adding reaction (1) to five times reaction (2) and then dividing the overall equation by 2:

\[
\begin{aligned}
&(1)\; 2\ce{MnO4^-}+10\ce{Cl^-}+16\ce{H^+}\rightarrow 2\ce{Mn^{2+}}+5\ce{Cl2}+8\ce{H2O}\qquad\Delta G_1^\ominus =-142.0\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}\\[4pt]
&5\,(2)\; 5\ce{Cl2}+10\ce{Fe^{2+}}\rightarrow 10\ce{Cl^-}+10\ce{Fe^{3+}}\qquad\Delta G_{2,5}^\ominus =5(-113.6) =-568.0\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}\\[4pt]
&\text{Add:}\; 2\ce{MnO4^-}+16\ce{H^+}+10\ce{Fe^{2+}}\rightarrow 2\ce{Mn^{2+}}+8\ce{H2O}+10\ce{Fe^{3+}}\\
&\text{Divide by 2:}\; \ce{MnO4^-}+8\ce{H^+}+5\ce{Fe^{2+}}\rightarrow\ce{Mn^{2+}}+4\ce{H2O}+5\ce{Fe^{3+}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Hence  

\[
