The titration gives the number of acidic end‑groups, which corresponds to the number of polymer chains:

\[
n_{\text{KOH}} = C_{\text{KOH}}V_{\text{KOH}}
=0.0400\;\text{mol L}^{-1}\times6.81\times10^{-3}\;\text{L}
=2.72\times10^{-4}\;\text{mol}
\]

Since each PLA chain possesses one titratable acid end‑group, the amount of polymer chains is the same:

\[
n_{\text{chains}} = 2.72\times10^{-4}\;\text{mol}
\]

Hence the number‑average molar mass of the chains is

\[
\bar M = \frac{m_{\text{PLA}}}{n_{\text{chains}}}
       = \frac{0.1619\;\text{g}}{2.72\times10^{-4}\;\text{mol}}
       \approx 5.95\times10^{2}\;\text{g mol}^{-1}.
\]

The repeating unit of PLA (the lactyl unit) has a molar mass

\[
M_{\text{unit}} = \frac{C_3H_4O_2}{\text{unit}} = 72.06\;\text{g mol}^{-1}.
\]

Thus the average degree of polymerisation (average number of monomer units per chain) is

\[
\text{DP} = \frac{\bar M}{M_{\text{unit}}}
          = \frac{5.95\times10^{2}}{72.06}
          \approx 8.3.
\]

\[
\boxed{8.3}
\]

