The combustion reaction of liquid ethyl acetate is  

\[
\ce{C4H8O2(l) + 5 O2(g) -> 4 CO2(g) + 4 H2O(l)}
\]

The standard entropy change for this reaction is  

\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta S^\circ &=\bigl[4S^\circ(\ce{CO2})+4S^\circ(\ce{H2O})\bigr]
                 -\bigl[S^\circ(\ce{C4H8O2})+5S^\circ(\ce{O2})\bigr]   \\
&= \bigl[4(213.7)+4(69.9)\bigr]
   -\bigl[259.4+5(205.0)\bigr] \;\text{J K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1}\\
&= 1134.4 - 1284.4 = -150.0\;\text{J K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

Hence the standard Gibbs energy of combustion is  

\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta G^\circ_{\text{comb}} &= \Delta H^\circ_{\text{comb}}
                               -T\Delta S^\circ   \\
&= (-2231\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1})
   -\bigl[298\;\text{K}\times(-150.0\;\text{J K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1})\bigr]\\
&= -2231\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}+44.7\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}\\
&= -2186\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

Using \(\Delta G^\circ = \sum \nu \Delta G_f^\circ(\text{products}) -
\sum \nu \Delta G_f^\circ(\text{reactants})\),

\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta G_f^\circ(\ce{C4H8O2}) &=
\bigl[4\Delta G_f^\circ(\ce{CO2})+4\Delta G_f^\circ(\ce{H2O})\bigr]
-\Delta G^\circ_{\text{comb}} \\
&= \bigl[4(-394.36)+4(-237.13)\bigr]\text{kJ mol}^{-1}
   -(-2186\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1})\\
&= (-2525.96 + 2186)\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}\\
&\approx -339.7\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

Rounded to the appropriate number of significant figures:

\[
\boxed{-340}\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

